      <h1 class="article-title">Vietnamese Artisanal Cane Sugar: Golden Terroir from the Mekong Delta</h1>
      <p class="article-subtitle">From the alluvial plains of the Mekong Delta, where sugarcane has been cultivated for centuries, comes a golden unrefined sugar with a depth that industrial processing can never replicate — rich with natural molasses, trace minerals, and the unmistakable character of sun-drenched Vietnamese terroir.</p>
    </header>

    <div class="feature-image">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1581441363689-1f3c3c414635?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=1200" alt="Golden artisanal cane sugar from Ben Tre, Vietnam — unrefined, mineral-rich, and sun-dried" loading="eager" decoding="async" width="1200" height="675" />
    </div>

    <div class="article-body">
      <p class="lead">The Mekong Delta is famed for its rice, but its sugarcane heritage is no less significant. Ben Tre, often called "Coconut Land," is also home to artisanal sugar makers who cultivate a distinctive golden unrefined cane sugar prized by specialty food brands for its warm molasses notes, natural mineral character, and complete absence of additives. Greenie Vietnam connects these traditional producers with international buyers seeking an authentic, clean-label sweetener.</p>

      <h2>The Alluvial Advantage</h2>
      <p>Centuries of Mekong River sediment have created some of the world's most fertile soil. Sugarcane grown here absorbs a unique mineral profile — calcium, magnesium, potassium — that simply doesn't exist in other growing regions. The cane grows tall, dense, and rich with the accumulated nutrition of millennia.</p>

      <blockquote>
        <p><strong>Technical Note:</strong> Unlike highly processed cane juice products, unrefined cane sugar retains its valuable minerals. Mineral content typically registers 1.8–2.3%, including calcium, magnesium, potassium, and trace B-complex vitamins.</p>
      </blockquote>

      <p>Industrial sugar refining strips away everything except pure sucrose. Our approach is the opposite: we preserve nature's full design. The result is a golden, slightly moist sugar that actually <em>tastes</em> like something — warm toffee, caramel, and a hint of the Delta breeze.</p>

      <blockquote>
        <p>White sugar is sugarcane with its soul removed. Our golden sugar — this is the cane's true spirit.</p>
        <footer>— Nguyen Van Bay, third-generation sugar artisan, Ben Tre</footer>
      </blockquote>

      <h2 class="accent-green">Flavor Profile</h2>
      <p>Our Golden Cane has a distinct caramel character with subtle floral notes.</p>

      <figure class="image-float-right">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518546305927-5a4bbfe3a78b?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=600" alt="Artisanal evaporation in traditional cane sugar pans" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>The traditional evaporation process concentrates cane juice into a golden syrup — the critical step that defines the sugar's rich flavor profile.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <p>Unlike refined white sugar — which delivers a one-note burst of sweetness and disappears — our golden cane sugar evolves on the palate. It begins with a warm caramel sweetness, unfolds into subtle molasses and toffee notes, and finishes with a delicate floral undertone that speaks of its artisanal production method.</p>

      <p>This complexity enables clean-label appeal: it is produced entirely without additives, bleaching agents, or anti-caking chemicals (lacking sulphur dioxide, phosphoric acid, and calcium hydroxide used in refined sugar production). The color is its natural hue. The slight moisture is evidence of its unrefined state. This is sugar as it has been made for centuries — honest, unadulterated, and deeply flavorful.</p>
    </div>

