    <div class="article-body">
      <h3>The Process</h3>

      <h4 class="accent-green">I. Hand-Harvested from Alluvial Silty Loam</h4>
      <p>Sugarcane stalks are individually selected and cut by hand when the Brix (sugar content) reaches 20–23%. Machine harvesting is avoided to prevent soil compaction in the delicate alluvial fields.</p>

      <h4 class="accent-green">II. Cold-Pressed Juice Extraction</h4>
      <p>Within 24 hours of cutting, the stalks pass through traditional roller mills that extract the maximum juice while minimizing oxidation — critical for preserving the cane's natural aromatic compounds.</p>

      <h4 class="accent-green">III. Slow Evaporation</h4>
      <p>The fresh juice is clarified with a touch of lime (the mineral, not the fruit), then slowly simmered in open pans. Over 4–6 hours, water evaporates and the juice concentrates into a thick, fragrant syrup.</p>

      <h4 class="accent-green">IV. Hand-Crystallization</h4>
      <p>As the syrup reaches supersaturation, artisans stir it continuously with wooden paddles — a rhythmic practice that triggers controlled crystallization without industrial centrifuges. The moisture is reduced to a stable 1.5–2.5%.</p>

      <h2 class="accent-green">The Golden Complexity</h2>
      <p>Ben Tre golden cane sugar doesn't just sweeten — it adds character. On the nose, warm caramel and honeyed toffee with a whisper of meadow flowers. The first taste unfolds slowly — a mellow sweetness that builds rather than slaps, carrying molasses depth and a faint mineral quality. There's a subtle nuttiness reminiscent of browned butter, and the finish is clean with no bitter aftertaste. A quality that refined white sugar simply cannot replicate.</p>

